1
00:01:49,840 --> 00:01:51,831
(Snoring)

2
00:01:53,480 --> 00:01:57,075
Congressmen, we're now
flying over the heart of Berlin.

3
00:01:57,960 --> 00:01:59,951
Berlin.

4
00:02:01,720 --> 00:02:04,871
Over 75,000 tons of explosives
were dropped here.

5
00:02:04,920 --> 00:02:08,071
British Lancasters by night,
American Fortresses by day.

6
00:02:08,120 --> 00:02:11,908
I heard Russian artillery
had a little part in it too, if you don't mind.

7
00:02:11,960 --> 00:02:15,350
Sure they did and I wish
they'd pay us for all those cannons.

8
00:02:15,400 --> 00:02:19,188
Hey, quit juggling. Film like this
is good stuff around election time.

9
00:02:19,240 --> 00:02:20,832
The incumbent overseas.

10
00:02:20,880 --> 00:02:23,519
Pennecot, don't you want to see it?
Look at it.

11
00:02:23,560 --> 00:02:28,031
Like pack rats been gnawing at a hunk
of old mouldy Roquefort cheese.

12
00:02:28,080 --> 00:02:29,672
(Gags)

13
00:02:34,120 --> 00:02:37,430
Miss Frost? Congresswoman Frost?

14
00:02:37,480 --> 00:02:40,040
- Present.
- We're flying over Berlin.

15
00:02:42,640 --> 00:02:44,835
15 minutes ahead of schedule.

16
00:02:44,880 --> 00:02:47,235
Well, don't you want to see it?

17
00:02:47,280 --> 00:02:49,271
One thing at a time.

18
00:03:26,360 --> 00:03:30,148
You got quite a sight coming.
Looks like chicken innards at frying time.

19
00:03:30,200 --> 00:03:32,760
Considering the taxpayers' money
poured on it,

20
00:03:32,800 --> 00:03:35,189
I don't expect it to look like a lace Valentine.

21
00:03:39,280 --> 00:03:41,077
Golly.

22
00:03:46,120 --> 00:03:49,908
(Man) Well, that's rough doing.
That sure is rough doing.

23
00:03:54,240 --> 00:03:57,869
(2nd man) They ought to put in grass
and move in a herd of longhorn.

24
00:03:57,920 --> 00:04:01,356
Build up their industries.
Get those smokestacks belching again.

25
00:04:01,400 --> 00:04:04,551
- Not without organised labour.
- We got to feed the people.

26
00:04:04,600 --> 00:04:07,672
You can't keep a country
eating scraps out of garbage pails.

27
00:04:07,720 --> 00:04:10,871
I'm all for sending food,
only let 'em know where it's from.

28
00:04:10,920 --> 00:04:12,911
I object to dollar diplomacy.

29
00:04:12,960 --> 00:04:16,111
- But you don't mind sending food.
- There's a difference.

30
00:04:16,160 --> 00:04:18,720
If you give a hungry man bread,
that's democracy.

31
00:04:18,760 --> 00:04:21,593
If you leave the wrapper on, it's imperialism.

32
00:04:21,640 --> 00:04:25,235
Gentlemen, these are
very grave problems indeed

33
00:04:25,280 --> 00:04:28,431
but they don't happen to be
the problems of this committee.

34
00:04:28,480 --> 00:04:31,392
Perhaps I should remind you
why we were sent to Berlin,

35
00:04:31,440 --> 00:04:34,238
since our chairman,
Mr Pennecot of New Hampshire,

36
00:04:34,280 --> 00:04:38,398
has been indisposed ever since
we took off from Washington.

37
00:04:38,440 --> 00:04:42,558
We're here to investigate the morale
of American occupation troops,

38
00:04:42,600 --> 00:04:44,397
nothing else.

39
00:04:44,440 --> 00:04:47,830
12,000 of our boys are policing
that pest hole down below

40
00:04:47,880 --> 00:04:52,954
and according to reports, they are being
infected by a kind of moral malaria.

41
00:04:53,000 --> 00:04:57,630
It is our duty to their wives, their mothers,
their sisters, to find the facts.

42
00:04:57,680 --> 00:04:59,671
And if these reports are true,

43
00:04:59,720 --> 00:05:03,838
to fumigate that place with
all the insecticides at our disposal.

44
00:05:03,880 --> 00:05:07,759
If you'll pardon me,
we're approaching Tempelhof Airfield.

45
00:05:09,080 --> 00:05:12,231
(Man) Oh, God, if they haven't got
a reception out for us.

46
00:05:12,280 --> 00:05:14,077
(2nd man) A band and everything.

47
00:05:14,120 --> 00:05:16,315
(3rd man) They'll be glad to see home folks.

48
00:05:25,920 --> 00:05:30,755
Men, once more it is our honour and
privilege to welcome a visiting committee.

49
00:05:30,800 --> 00:05:35,157
Lately they seem to be coming
as regularly as the electric bill.

50
00:05:35,200 --> 00:05:37,555
This time it's not just VIPs.

51
00:05:37,600 --> 00:05:40,319
This time we're getting VIPls.

52
00:05:40,360 --> 00:05:43,079
Very lmportant Persons Indeed.

53
00:05:43,120 --> 00:05:47,591
Some Congressional committee
to investigate our morale.

54
00:05:47,640 --> 00:05:52,111
Seems back home, they've got an idea
this here is one great big picnic,

55
00:05:52,160 --> 00:05:55,550
that all we do is swing in hammocks
with blonde Fruleins,

56
00:05:55,600 --> 00:05:57,670
swap cigarettes for castles on the Rhine

57
00:05:57,720 --> 00:06:00,280
and soak our feet in sparkling Mosel.

58
00:06:00,320 --> 00:06:02,390
Well, let's not kid ourselves.

59
00:06:02,440 --> 00:06:05,159
Some of you do go
overboard once in a while.

60
00:06:05,200 --> 00:06:09,318
Maybe some of you are working too hard
to enlighten the civilian population

61
00:06:09,360 --> 00:06:12,079
and maybe some of you
PX millionaires have found out

62
00:06:12,120 --> 00:06:16,238
you can parlay a pack of cigarettes
into something more than 20 smokes.

63
00:06:16,280 --> 00:06:19,192
After all, this isn't a Boy Scout camp.

64
00:06:19,240 --> 00:06:21,037
We've got a tough job on our hands

65
00:06:21,080 --> 00:06:24,231
and, by and large,
I think we're handling it darn well.

66
00:06:24,280 --> 00:06:26,919
For my dough, we're on the ball.

67
00:06:26,960 --> 00:06:29,679
Most of us, anyway... most of the time.

68
00:06:29,720 --> 00:06:35,511
What they've got to realise is you can't pin
sergeant's stripes on an archangel.

69
00:06:35,560 --> 00:06:38,472
Now, this committee
is going to be here for five days.

70
00:06:38,520 --> 00:06:41,239
Let's give them as good
an impression as possible.

71
00:06:41,280 --> 00:06:43,999
Not pussyfooting
around with a phoney attitude.

72
00:06:44,040 --> 00:06:46,600
That's not fair to them or us.

73
00:06:46,640 --> 00:06:49,552
I'm counting on you men to behave, period.

74
00:06:50,920 --> 00:06:54,469
Morale. Maybe some day we can send
a little committee of our own

75
00:06:54,520 --> 00:06:56,875
to investigate morale in Washington, DC.

76
00:07:01,520 --> 00:07:05,638
Hey, look what I picked up
at the Brandenburg Gate.

77
00:07:07,040 --> 00:07:09,235
- How much?
- A dozen candy bars.

78
00:07:10,080 --> 00:07:12,275
They've still got some nine and a halfs.

79
00:07:12,320 --> 00:07:14,675
- I got no one to give them to.
- How about Trudy?

80
00:07:14,720 --> 00:07:18,315
I lost her. Russian sergeant came along
with a pound of rancid butter.

81
00:07:18,360 --> 00:07:21,511
- Those German dames are all alike.
- Speak for yourself.

82
00:07:21,560 --> 00:07:25,348
I wouldn't be afraid
of a Russian general with a ton of caviar.

83
00:07:26,280 --> 00:07:28,077
Nice toe.

84
00:07:30,400 --> 00:07:32,197
The best.

85
00:07:41,400 --> 00:07:43,595
We're here, Congressman.
Ready to unload?

86
00:07:45,960 --> 00:07:48,155
(J Upbeat march)

87
00:07:53,920 --> 00:07:56,309
(Drill sergeant) Present... arms!

88
00:08:13,600 --> 00:08:15,989
- Hello, Colonel.
- Nice to see you, General.

89
00:08:16,040 --> 00:08:20,158
Mr Giffin from Texas, General Finney,
General McAndrew, Colonel Plummer.

90
00:08:20,200 --> 00:08:22,395
- My pleasure.
- Mr Salvatore, from New York.

91
00:08:22,440 --> 00:08:25,876
- The Bronx.
- Nobody's going to think you're Wall Street.

92
00:08:25,920 --> 00:08:29,879
Mr Yandell, Congressman from Virginia.
Mr Kraus, Congressman from Illinois.

93
00:08:29,920 --> 00:08:33,515
Hold it, everybody.
Want to get some of this brass.

94
00:08:33,560 --> 00:08:35,357
Snappy little outfit you have.

95
00:08:35,400 --> 00:08:37,595
Thank you. I have to apologise for the band.

96
00:08:37,640 --> 00:08:40,632
- You should indeed.
- We're half strength today.

97
00:08:40,680 --> 00:08:43,240
- We generally have 40 pieces.
- That's terrible.

98
00:08:43,280 --> 00:08:47,193
We sent the others to the British sector
for a parade. It's Empire Day.

99
00:08:47,240 --> 00:08:51,711
What's terrible is I came hoping to find
an army taking its task with seriousness.

100
00:08:51,760 --> 00:08:54,115
Instead I find you have a 40-piece band.

101
00:08:54,160 --> 00:08:56,515
Perhaps you also have
some drum majorettes.

102
00:08:56,560 --> 00:08:58,073
- May I introduce...
- I know.

103
00:08:58,120 --> 00:09:01,112
General Finney, General McAndrew
and Colonel Plummer.

104
00:09:01,160 --> 00:09:04,948
It's in my data. I am Miss Frost,
Congresswoman from lowa, 9th district.

105
00:09:05,000 --> 00:09:08,595
Delightful of Congress to send us
a lady representative for a change.

106
00:09:08,640 --> 00:09:09,755
Delightful.

107
00:09:09,800 --> 00:09:13,395
May I suggest here and now that
we dispense with all the soft soap.

108
00:09:13,440 --> 00:09:16,591
As committee chairman,
permit me to bring you greetings

109
00:09:16,640 --> 00:09:19,552
from the people
of the United States of America.

110
00:09:19,600 --> 00:09:24,435
This genial reception augurs well
for the success of our mission.

111
00:09:24,480 --> 00:09:29,076
I sincerely hope so. And now let us proceed
to a luncheon we have prepared for you.

112
00:09:29,120 --> 00:09:33,750
A very simple luncheon. Powdered egg
omelette, probably, and a little Spam.

113
00:09:40,720 --> 00:09:43,075
- Can I carry that for you?
- No, thank you.

114
00:09:43,120 --> 00:09:46,715
I undertook to deliver it in person
to a Captain John Pringle,

115
00:09:46,760 --> 00:09:49,115
stationed somewhere in Berlin, G2 Section.

116
00:09:49,160 --> 00:09:52,152
- Could you tell me how to go about it?
- I could try.

117
00:09:52,200 --> 00:09:55,510
Through army channels?
All I have is five days.

118
00:09:55,560 --> 00:09:56,629
Captain Pringle!

119
00:09:58,040 --> 00:09:59,837
Captain Pringle!

120
00:10:03,760 --> 00:10:05,512
Captain Pringle reporting, sir.

121
00:10:05,560 --> 00:10:08,279
Congresswoman Frost,
this is Captain Pringle.

122
00:10:08,320 --> 00:10:11,710
Thank you. This is for you,
Captain Pringle. Happy birthday.

123
00:10:11,760 --> 00:10:15,196
Or happy birthday yesterday.
I thought I could deliver it on time

124
00:10:15,240 --> 00:10:18,391
but we were held up
in Newfoundland for 16 hours - fog.

125
00:10:18,440 --> 00:10:21,796
- You brought this from America?
- Murdoch, lowa.

126
00:10:21,840 --> 00:10:24,035
Well, how is good old lowa?

127
00:10:24,080 --> 00:10:26,071
62%% % Republican, thank you.

128
00:10:26,120 --> 00:10:30,511
I was entrusted with this by a constituent,
or rather, his daughter.

129
00:10:30,560 --> 00:10:33,120
I hope it's still in one piece. Open it.

130
00:10:33,160 --> 00:10:34,957
Be glad.

131
00:10:43,920 --> 00:10:46,480
Well, what do you know? Little Dusty.

132
00:10:48,720 --> 00:10:50,517
It's a beauty.

133
00:10:50,560 --> 00:10:52,551
I didn't know it was so personal.

134
00:10:52,600 --> 00:10:56,991
Her name is really Pauline Rose
but we call her Dusty. Some joke.

135
00:10:57,040 --> 00:11:00,635
- How long since you've seen her?
- Dusty? Four years.

136
00:11:00,680 --> 00:11:04,116
Don't these boys ever get home?
Can't they be given a short leave?

137
00:11:04,160 --> 00:11:07,072
- Certainly, if it's accrued.
- I don't want any leave.

138
00:11:07,120 --> 00:11:10,112
- You don't?
- Oh, of course I do. Dying to.

139
00:11:10,160 --> 00:11:13,118
We're all homesick
but personal feelings don't matter.

140
00:11:13,160 --> 00:11:15,151
There's unfinished business here.

141
00:11:15,200 --> 00:11:18,351
Now that we've won the war,
we mustn't lose the peace.

142
00:11:18,400 --> 00:11:21,949
I hate to think of anybody
sitting in his lonely barracks

143
00:11:22,000 --> 00:11:23,797
with a birthday cake on his knees.

144
00:11:23,840 --> 00:11:26,991
I won't have the cake on my knees.
I won't be alone.

145
00:11:28,000 --> 00:11:30,355
There'll be my buddies. I'll call them in.

146
00:11:30,400 --> 00:11:33,551
We'll open up a case of root beer,
light the candles,

147
00:11:33,600 --> 00:11:35,716
then Frankovitch and his ukulele.

148
00:11:35,760 --> 00:11:39,878
Some old songs.
Why, it'll be like back home... almost.

149
00:11:39,920 --> 00:11:41,672
Good to hear you talk like that.

150
00:11:41,720 --> 00:11:43,790
General Finney wants you to go in his car.

151
00:11:43,840 --> 00:11:45,239
I'll be right with you.

152
00:11:45,280 --> 00:11:49,831
If you're a sample of the spirit
prevailing in Berlin, I feel better already.

153
00:11:49,880 --> 00:11:52,235
- I'm a sample, all right.
- Goodbye.

154
00:11:57,320 --> 00:11:59,959
You're losing something, Captain Pringle.

155
00:12:00,880 --> 00:12:02,472
My handkerchief.

156
00:12:02,520 --> 00:12:04,875
You blow your nose in nylon nowadays?

157
00:12:07,360 --> 00:12:10,955
What do you know? There must have
been a mistake at the laundry.

158
00:12:11,000 --> 00:12:14,595
We got a crazy old laundress.
You know what happened to Frankovitch?

159
00:12:14,640 --> 00:12:18,155
He sent out his shorts and got back a girdle.
(Laughs)

160
00:12:19,200 --> 00:12:21,077
(Groans)

161
00:12:36,960 --> 00:12:38,951
Ask her how much.

162
00:12:39,000 --> 00:12:43,630
(Speaking German)

163
00:12:43,680 --> 00:12:45,671
800 cigarettes, or coffee.

164
00:12:46,640 --> 00:12:49,552
(Speaking German)

165
00:13:06,360 --> 00:13:10,148
No. This watch gold. Gold for teeth.

166
00:13:10,200 --> 00:13:12,395
- A watch from steel.
- How's this?

167
00:13:12,440 --> 00:13:15,000
No, this silver. Want steel.

168
00:13:15,040 --> 00:13:16,837
You want steel.

169
00:13:16,880 --> 00:13:20,998
No, want round watch, very big, nice face.

170
00:13:21,040 --> 00:13:24,828
You're tough. All right,
let's look in the other drawer.

171
00:13:26,720 --> 00:13:30,235
(Cackles) Mickey Mouse! Mickey Mouse!

172
00:13:30,280 --> 00:13:32,271
- How much?
- $700.

173
00:13:33,280 --> 00:13:36,590
- You got three like this watch, maybe?
- We'll see.

174
00:13:45,560 --> 00:13:49,838
Herr Captain, buy porcelain?
Little Cupid to take for wife?

175
00:13:49,880 --> 00:13:52,872
Never mind the knick-knacks.
How much for the mattress?

176
00:13:52,920 --> 00:13:55,718
- Why you want the mattress?
- I'm sleepy.

177
00:13:55,760 --> 00:13:59,036
- How much for the mattress?
- (Speaking German)

178
00:14:00,960 --> 00:14:03,155
What do you mean, "nein, nein, no"?

179
00:14:03,200 --> 00:14:05,156
Look what you can get for it.

180
00:14:05,200 --> 00:14:08,078
(Speaking German)

181
00:14:09,600 --> 00:14:12,751
12 eggs in it and look at
the writing on it and the candles.

182
00:14:12,800 --> 00:14:16,190
The candles alone are worth the mattress.
Get lost.

183
00:14:16,240 --> 00:14:18,310
(All speaking German)

184
00:15:38,360 --> 00:15:40,351
(Brakes squeal)

185
00:15:40,400 --> 00:15:42,391
(Honks horn)

186
00:16:11,120 --> 00:16:13,111
Yoo-hoo!

187
00:16:14,080 --> 00:16:16,833
Erika! Erika!

188
00:16:27,240 --> 00:16:29,231
(Whistling cheerfully)

189
00:16:32,600 --> 00:16:34,556
(Speaks German)

190
00:16:35,680 --> 00:16:38,240
Sit down, Johnny.

191
00:16:43,040 --> 00:16:45,031
Go away, Johnny, sit down.

192
00:17:03,560 --> 00:17:05,152
Johnny.

193
00:17:05,200 --> 00:17:07,555
Johnny, what are you doing?

194
00:17:07,600 --> 00:17:10,637
- I'm wiping my face.
- You're hurting me, Johnny.

195
00:17:10,680 --> 00:17:13,831
You're always hurting me.
Why are you so mean to me?

196
00:17:13,880 --> 00:17:17,077
I worry about you. I scrounge around,
I bring you presents

197
00:17:17,120 --> 00:17:18,758
and you tell me I'm mean to you.

198
00:17:18,800 --> 00:17:22,588
You brought me a present? Where is it?
Where have you got it?

199
00:17:22,640 --> 00:17:24,676
Ohh...

200
00:17:24,720 --> 00:17:28,838
Johnny, they're so sheer. So beautiful.

201
00:17:28,880 --> 00:17:32,031
52 gauge. So I'm mean to you?

202
00:17:32,080 --> 00:17:35,231
- No, you're good to me.
- You bet I am.

203
00:17:35,280 --> 00:17:39,398
You don't know how good. I bought
you another present. You're not gonna get it.

204
00:17:39,440 --> 00:17:42,591
Another one? Where have you got it?
Where is it, Johnny?

205
00:17:42,640 --> 00:17:45,473
- Keep away.
- Is it here? Tell me...

206
00:17:46,760 --> 00:17:50,992
Johnny... (Speaks German)

207
00:17:51,040 --> 00:17:53,759
- Where did you get it?
- A friend of mine baked it.

208
00:17:53,800 --> 00:17:57,588
Only you're not going to get it. Why
should I care whether you sleep or not?

209
00:17:57,640 --> 00:18:01,519
Johnny, for 15 years
we haven't slept in Germany.

210
00:18:01,560 --> 00:18:04,950
First it was Hitler screaming on the radio,
then the war of nerves,

211
00:18:05,000 --> 00:18:07,195
then the victory celebrations,

212
00:18:07,240 --> 00:18:09,231
then the bombing.

213
00:18:09,280 --> 00:18:11,271
All the furniture burnt.

214
00:18:11,320 --> 00:18:13,117
See?

215
00:18:13,160 --> 00:18:15,116
(Springs crash and boing)

216
00:18:15,160 --> 00:18:18,470
That one I hate worst.
Give me that mattress, Johnny.

217
00:18:18,520 --> 00:18:20,511
No mattress will help you sleep.

218
00:18:20,560 --> 00:18:22,949
What you Germans need
is a better conscience.

219
00:18:23,000 --> 00:18:24,797
I have a good conscience.

220
00:18:24,840 --> 00:18:27,991
I have a new Fhrer now... you.

221
00:18:28,040 --> 00:18:29,314
Heil, Johnny.

222
00:18:29,360 --> 00:18:31,999
You heil me once more
and I'll knock your teeth in.

223
00:18:32,040 --> 00:18:33,837
You'll bruise your lips.

224
00:18:33,880 --> 00:18:37,031
Why don't I choke you a little?
Break you in two?

225
00:18:37,840 --> 00:18:40,559
Build a fire under you, you blonde witch.

226
00:18:40,600 --> 00:18:42,033
(Knock at door)

227
00:18:42,080 --> 00:18:43,672
Who's that?

228
00:18:43,720 --> 00:18:45,711
With my luck, it's Eisenhower.

229
00:18:54,600 --> 00:18:56,591
- Yes.
- Your name Schltow?

230
00:18:56,640 --> 00:18:59,359
- I beg your pardon.
- Is your name Erika Schltow?

231
00:18:59,400 --> 00:19:01,391
- No.
- You live here, don't you?

232
00:19:01,440 --> 00:19:02,839
Yes, I live here.

233
00:19:02,880 --> 00:19:05,678
You the dame that sings
at the Lorelei nightclub?

234
00:19:05,720 --> 00:19:09,315
- Yes, I sing there.
- And your name's not Erika Schltow?

235
00:19:10,360 --> 00:19:12,999
My name is Erika von Schltow.

236
00:19:13,040 --> 00:19:15,031
- A von?
- She's a von.

237
00:19:15,080 --> 00:19:17,878
Nobility. We beg your highness's pardon.

238
