They'll steal anything around here.

481
00:36:05,640 --> 00:36:09,235
- When I think of that girl back in lowa...
- Yeah.

482
00:36:09,280 --> 00:36:11,840
I'll take care of this. Don't trouble yourself.

483
00:36:11,880 --> 00:36:15,998
Thank you. Will you also take care
of a pair of disgusting soldiers

484
00:36:16,040 --> 00:36:18,759
who should be stood up against a wall and...

485
00:36:19,760 --> 00:36:21,159
Oh.

486
00:36:21,200 --> 00:36:25,273
I want you to find them.
They're medium height. One is a little taller.

487
00:36:25,320 --> 00:36:29,438
Their names are Mike and Joe and
they're in uniforms with US on the collar.

488
00:36:29,480 --> 00:36:30,754
Perfect sense, ma'am.

489
00:36:30,800 --> 00:36:33,314
Now, what exactly is
the name of this sewer?

490
00:36:33,360 --> 00:36:34,918
- The Lorelei.
- Address?

491
00:36:34,960 --> 00:36:38,475
- Number 15, Hagenbachstrae.
- Are there other sewers like this?

492
00:36:38,520 --> 00:36:42,035
- Three or four but this is the best.
- What is the name of that woman?

493
00:36:42,080 --> 00:36:43,798
- What woman?
- The singer here.

494
00:36:43,840 --> 00:36:46,877
Oh, the singer. I think it's Erika.

495
00:36:46,920 --> 00:36:50,310
- Erika what?
- Erika von Schltow.

496
00:36:50,360 --> 00:36:51,759
Why do you ask about her?

497
00:36:51,800 --> 00:36:56,271
Because there's something funny going on
here and I'm not in the mood for laughs.

498
00:36:56,320 --> 00:36:58,515
Schltow? How do you spell it?

499
00:36:58,560 --> 00:37:00,551
Schltow, with an umlaut.

500
00:37:00,600 --> 00:37:02,591
I thought so.

501
00:37:05,880 --> 00:37:08,678
I want you to remember
that when we moved into Germany,

502
00:37:08,720 --> 00:37:11,632
we found a country of
open graves and closed hearts.

503
00:37:11,680 --> 00:37:14,478
We've tried to turn it into a civilised state.

504
00:37:14,520 --> 00:37:18,115
We had to eliminate things
that breed unrest and aggression.

505
00:37:18,160 --> 00:37:21,311
We've tried to make them free men
and give them some dignity.

506
00:37:21,360 --> 00:37:25,148
We had to return four million
displaced persons to their homes.

507
00:37:25,200 --> 00:37:27,839
That's hard if you don't have
a home to start with.

508
00:37:27,880 --> 00:37:30,917
We had to repair hospitals
and public utilities.

509
00:37:30,960 --> 00:37:34,350
I remember the first day the gasworks
started operating again.

510
00:37:34,400 --> 00:37:37,790
There were 160 suicides in Berlin alone.

511
00:37:37,840 --> 00:37:39,637
That was ten months ago.

512
00:37:39,680 --> 00:37:43,798
Today, they take a match and light
the gas and boil some potatoes.

513
00:37:43,840 --> 00:37:47,435
Not many potatoes, mind you.
There is still a lot of hunger.

514
00:37:47,480 --> 00:37:49,596
But there is a new will to live.

515
00:37:49,640 --> 00:37:54,111
We had to build schools and find teachers
and then teach the teachers.

516
00:37:54,160 --> 00:37:58,278
We helped them start a free press
and institute a parliamentary government.

517
00:37:58,320 --> 00:38:00,880
They had their first free election in 14 years.

518
00:38:00,920 --> 00:38:03,354
It had been so long
they didn't know what to do.

519
00:38:03,400 --> 00:38:06,551
It was like handing
the village drunk a glass of water.

520
00:38:07,560 --> 00:38:12,031
What I want to point out is that
it's a tough, thankless, lonely job.

521
00:38:12,080 --> 00:38:14,275
We're trying to lick it as well as we can.

522
00:38:14,320 --> 00:38:17,710
You might as well know,
some of us get out of line occasionally.

523
00:38:17,760 --> 00:38:20,320
But remember this.
For the first time in history,

524
00:38:20,360 --> 00:38:24,990
you are asking the same generation of
soldiers to be both valorous and wise.

525
00:38:25,040 --> 00:38:26,837
- Mighty fine.
- Well said.

526
00:38:26,880 --> 00:38:30,475
I sure hope our chairman has
made notes of that speech of yours.

527
00:38:30,520 --> 00:38:33,159
I think it should be
incorporated in our report.

528
00:38:33,200 --> 00:38:36,351
Colonel, we buy every word of it, all of us.

529
00:38:36,400 --> 00:38:37,913
I don't.

530
00:38:38,880 --> 00:38:43,317
I wouldn't think of buying it. I'm surprised
at my colleagues' low sales resistance.

531
00:38:43,360 --> 00:38:46,750
Miss Frost, this attitude calls
for some explanation.

532
00:38:46,800 --> 00:38:48,995
Colonel Plummer, in your eloquent speech,

533
00:38:49,040 --> 00:38:51,235
which I'm sure you've made 50 times,

534
00:38:51,280 --> 00:38:55,068
you used the phrase "Some of our boys
may get out of line sometimes."

535
00:38:55,120 --> 00:38:57,315
That is a masterpiece of understatement.

536
00:38:57,360 --> 00:38:58,873
What are you driving at?

537
00:38:58,920 --> 00:39:03,550
In your effort to civilise this country,
our boys are becoming barbarians.

538
00:39:03,600 --> 00:39:06,751
- I explained on that tour...
- I know all about those tours.

539
00:39:06,800 --> 00:39:11,191
You put blinkers on us and make sure
we only see what you want us to see.

540
00:39:11,240 --> 00:39:14,835
Then you give us pamphlets,
statistics, a rousing speech

541
00:39:14,880 --> 00:39:17,872
and ship us back a little more
bamboozled than when we came.

542
00:39:17,920 --> 00:39:20,639
We could have learned
as much from Reader's Digest.

543
00:39:20,680 --> 00:39:24,070
- This is very embarrassing, Colonel.
- Go on, Miss Frost.

544
00:39:24,120 --> 00:39:26,953
Well, I don't like blinkers.
I look in all directions

545
00:39:27,000 --> 00:39:31,437
and when I suspect dirt's been swept
under a carpet, I turn up that carpet.

546
00:39:31,480 --> 00:39:34,631
- What carpet? What dirt?
- What dirt?

547
00:39:34,680 --> 00:39:38,912
- One day and this is filled with it.
- Please particularise.

548
00:39:38,960 --> 00:39:41,679
Gls consorting with German Fruleins...

549
00:39:41,720 --> 00:39:43,153
Fraternisation is legal.

550
00:39:43,200 --> 00:39:46,875
...in wide-open, shameless,
black-market nightclubs.

551
00:39:47,880 --> 00:39:51,668
So we close them and our boys sneak off
to places in the Russian sector,

552
00:39:51,720 --> 00:39:54,757
or the British, or in the French,
and there's another thing.

553
00:39:54,800 --> 00:39:57,837
This is off the record.
Those places attract a lot of scum

554
00:39:57,880 --> 00:40:01,475
and we clean it up by cracking down
with a surprise raid once in a while.

555
00:40:01,520 --> 00:40:05,638
Notorious Nazi entertainers parading
themselves before our boys,

556
00:40:05,680 --> 00:40:08,592
- is that off the record too?
- For instance?

557
00:40:08,640 --> 00:40:13,031
I am specifically referring
to one Erika von Schltow,

558
00:40:13,080 --> 00:40:18,074
who works at a dive called the Lorelei,
15 Hagenbachstrae.

559
00:40:18,120 --> 00:40:19,678
How can a creature...

560
00:40:24,880 --> 00:40:27,440
I insist on a satisfactory explanation.

561
00:40:27,480 --> 00:40:31,268
I must ask the Congresswoman
to drop this particular matter.

562
00:40:31,320 --> 00:40:34,517
- Why?
- Some things must be left to our discretion.

563
00:40:34,560 --> 00:40:39,031
Colonel Plummer, I didn't go for
the blinkers. Now, don't try a muzzle.

564
00:40:39,080 --> 00:40:42,470
The last time someone wanted to gag me,
he tried it with a mink coat

565
00:40:42,520 --> 00:40:48,072
but I never let go until the president of that
particular ship company wound up in jail,

566
00:40:48,120 --> 00:40:51,112
even though I did get
pneumonia that winter.

567
00:40:53,640 --> 00:40:56,632
Herr Maier, this is the second time
we've had complaints.

568
00:40:56,680 --> 00:40:59,956
I don't think it's a good idea
that your son... What's his name?

569
00:41:00,000 --> 00:41:01,035
Gerhard.

570
00:41:01,080 --> 00:41:05,551
That Gerhard should draw swastikas
all over the neighbourhood.

571
00:41:05,600 --> 00:41:07,909
(Chastises in German)

572
00:41:07,960 --> 00:41:11,236
- I will break his arm.
- We've dissolved the Gestapo.

573
00:41:11,280 --> 00:41:15,751
No food, Brschchen.
I will lock him into a dark room.

574
00:41:15,800 --> 00:41:17,791
Why not just shove him in a gas chamber?

575
00:41:17,840 --> 00:41:18,875
Yes, Herr Kapitn.

576
00:41:18,920 --> 00:41:21,639
Listen, we've done away
with concentration camps.

577
00:41:21,680 --> 00:41:25,036
Take him round to a G YA,
one of our German youth clubs.

578
00:41:25,080 --> 00:41:28,675
Some baseball and a little less
heel-clicking is what he needs.

579
00:41:28,720 --> 00:41:30,915
Here's the address. Ask for Sergeant Breen.

580
00:41:30,960 --> 00:41:32,757
Yes, Herr Kapitn.

581
00:41:33,560 --> 00:41:36,358
I mean, thank you, Herr Kapitn.

582
00:41:36,400 --> 00:41:38,277
Auf wiedersehen.

583
00:41:38,320 --> 00:41:40,311
Come, Brschchen.

584
00:41:47,120 --> 00:41:50,112
- Captain Pringle is wanted in 112.
- Who's that?

585
00:41:50,160 --> 00:41:52,720
That Congress dame,
whatever her name is.

586
00:41:52,760 --> 00:41:54,352
- Wants to see me?
- You, sir.

587
00:41:54,400 --> 00:41:56,595
- Now?
- Now. She's clucking like a hen.

588
00:41:56,640 --> 00:41:59,757
You'd better get there
before she lays an egg.

589
00:42:15,640 --> 00:42:18,200
- Captain Pringle reporting.
- Hello.

590
00:42:19,000 --> 00:42:22,197
- Lorelei, how do you spell it?
- Lorelei?

591
00:42:22,240 --> 00:42:24,231
L-E or E-I at the end?

592
00:42:24,280 --> 00:42:25,872
E-I.

593
00:42:25,920 --> 00:42:27,717
Thank you.

594
00:42:30,160 --> 00:42:34,278
Captain Pringle, my belief in the army
has been shaken to the core.

595
00:42:34,320 --> 00:42:37,517
- Really?
- I can't trust anybody in uniform.

596
00:42:37,560 --> 00:42:39,118
Now, please...

597
00:42:39,160 --> 00:42:41,720
With one single exception, you.

598
00:42:42,680 --> 00:42:43,795
Thank you, ma'am.

599
00:42:43,840 --> 00:42:46,035
I trust you because we're both lowans.

600
00:42:46,080 --> 00:42:49,675
- Right back at you, Miss Frost.
- Moreover, you're a hard worker.

601
00:42:49,720 --> 00:42:52,075
Perhaps you work too hard. You look tired.

602
00:42:52,120 --> 00:42:54,315
Well, I hoped it didn't show.

603
00:42:55,960 --> 00:42:58,315
That is ink, Captain Pringle.

604
00:42:58,360 --> 00:42:59,588
So it is.

605
00:42:59,640 --> 00:43:01,119
Captain, I need your help.

606
00:43:01,160 --> 00:43:04,994
I want some additional data
on Frulein von Schltow.

607
00:43:05,040 --> 00:43:06,473
The one with the umlaut.

608
00:43:06,520 --> 00:43:10,149
- Oh, her.
- There must be a file on that woman.

609
00:43:10,200 --> 00:43:13,795
- Of course there is. Only it's not here.
- It isn't?

610
00:43:13,840 --> 00:43:16,479
I asked for it
and I was told it's gone to Nrnberg.

611
00:43:16,520 --> 00:43:19,671
On account of the trials,
a lot of files have been sent there.

612
00:43:19,720 --> 00:43:21,517
- I see.
- I asked around, though.

613
00:43:21,560 --> 00:43:24,393
- Did you find anything?
- Nothing important. Gossip.

614
00:43:24,440 --> 00:43:27,079
Are you sure? No fire with all that smoke?

615
00:43:27,120 --> 00:43:30,032
She may have known
a couple of minor party members.

616
00:43:30,080 --> 00:43:32,878
Nothing worth your attention.
Small fry, I'd say.

617
00:43:32,920 --> 00:43:35,559
- All right, ma'am, we're ready to go.
- Thank you.

618
00:43:35,600 --> 00:43:38,592
A warrant officer said he'd seen her
in an old newsreel,

619
00:43:38,640 --> 00:43:41,200
so I sent for the film from the Signal Corp.

620
00:43:45,400 --> 00:43:47,197
(Pringle) The Week In Pictures.

621
00:43:50,040 --> 00:43:53,191
This is a little Nazi get-together in Breslau.

622
00:43:58,520 --> 00:44:02,308
That's Goebbels telling them
how they're winning the war.

623
00:44:07,000 --> 00:44:09,912
Opening of the opera with Lohengrin
and famous guests.

624
00:44:09,960 --> 00:44:12,349
(Frost) They fiddled big while Berlin burned.

625
00:44:12,400 --> 00:44:15,073
Lohengrin, you know, swan song.

626
00:44:18,560 --> 00:44:23,236
(Frost) Now we're getting someplace.
I wonder what holds up that dress.

627
00:44:23,280 --> 00:44:25,794
(Pringle) Must be that German willpower.

628
00:44:25,840 --> 00:44:28,274
(Frost) Who's that man?
(Pringle) I think it's Birgel.

629
00:44:28,320 --> 00:44:30,788
(Frost) Who?
(Pringle) Hans Otto Birgel.

630
00:44:30,840 --> 00:44:32,831
(Frost) Who is Hans Otto Birgel?

631
00:44:32,880 --> 00:44:36,316
(Pringle) He had something to do
with the Gestapo. He's dead.

632
00:44:36,360 --> 00:44:42,037
- Killed himself when the Russians came.
- (Frost) An important party member?

633
00:44:42,080 --> 00:44:43,877
(Pringle) So-so.

634
00:44:43,920 --> 00:44:46,878
(Frost) Well, she must be his girlfriend.

635
00:44:46,920 --> 00:44:49,559
Maybe she doesn't know him.
Maybe she had a dizzy spell

636
00:44:49,600 --> 00:44:52,478
and the first thing she could catch
was his... elbow.

637
00:45:17,920 --> 00:45:20,115
(Frost) That's enough. Thank you.

638
00:45:22,280 --> 00:45:26,273
Well, we've learned one thing.
No small fry is she.

639
00:45:26,320 --> 00:45:29,357
- I guess not.
- That a Nazi woman like that should...

640
00:45:29,400 --> 00:45:32,551
I'll see she discontinues
her appearances as an entertainer.

641
00:45:32,600 --> 00:45:34,795
- Will that be satisfactory?
- It will not.

642
00:45:34,840 --> 00:45:37,400
What would you suggest, shave her head?

643
00:45:37,440 --> 00:45:39,032
- I'm not after her head.
- Well?

644
00:45:39,080 --> 00:45:42,675
It's common talk that an officer
in the army is protecting her.

645
00:45:42,720 --> 00:45:46,110
- It's his head I'm after.
- You really think an officer?

646
00:45:46,160 --> 00:45:47,957
Incredible as it may seem.

647
00:45:48,000 --> 00:45:50,195
Now, let's use some common sense.

648
00:45:50,240 --> 00:45:53,835
That man is not giving her
his protection for platonic reasons.

649
00:45:53,880 --> 00:45:55,871
- Granted?
- Granted.

650
00:45:55,920 --> 00:45:58,275
Of course the association is undercover.

651
00:45:58,320 --> 00:46:01,232
He's not stupid enough
to entertain her at his billet.

652
00:46:01,280 --> 00:46:05,068
- I guess that's right.
- We can therefore assume he visits her.

653
00:46:05,120 --> 00:46:07,111
Very logical.

654
00:46:07,160 --> 00:46:10,550
Therefore, to catch him,
we must watch her place.

655
00:46:10,600 --> 00:46:12,397
Smart idea.

656
00:46:12,440 --> 00:46:15,159
- You know where she lives?
- I can find out.

657
00:46:15,200 --> 00:46:18,351
And I shall watch it
day and night... personally.

658
00:46:18,400 --> 00:46:20,960
No, we'll watch it together, the two of us.

659
00:46:21,000 --> 00:46:24,390
- We will?
- Yes. I want to be an eyewitness.

660
00:46:24,440 --> 00:46:27,876
I want to see that man myself
and face him down.

661
00:46:27,920 --> 00:46:30,275
Can you afford the time, Miss Frost?

662
00:46:30,320 --> 00:46:33,915
Any time it requires.
This I intend to make my case in point.

663
00:46:33,960 --> 00:46:35,757
You'll go to the General?

664
00:46:35,800 --> 00:46:39,793
I will, and to the War Department
and to the President.

665
00:46:40,640 --> 00:46:43,791
And if that doesn't do it,
I'll see Gabriel Heater.

666
00:46:55,640 --> 00:46:59,030
It's well after curfew.
I wonder if he's coming tonight.

667
00:46:59,080 --> 00:47:01,799
- He'll be here.
- Yeah?

668
00:47:01,840 --> 00:47:05,116
I don't think you understand
about arrangements like this.

669
00:47:05,160 --> 00:47:07,720
They work 24 hours a day,
seven days a week.

670
00:47:07,760 --> 00:47:09,751
Does the CIO know about this?

671
00:47:12,920 --> 00:47:16,071
Are you sure there aren't
any back stairs to that apartment?

672
00:47:16,120 --> 00:47:17,712
There isn't even any back wall.

673
00:47:17,760 --> 00:47:20,752
She must be waiting for somebody.
Why leave the lights on?

674
00:47:20,800 --> 00:47:23,872
Maybe she's knitting
or putting up pickled peaches.

675
00:47:24,480 --> 00:47:26,471
Only we know better.

676
00:47:31,080 --> 00:47:33,036
Pickled peaches.

677
00:47:34,200 --> 00:47:37,749
I bet you miss lowa. I do already.

678
00:47:39,200 --> 00:47:42,351
- It's changed since you've been there.
- Yeah?

679
00:47:42,400 --> 00:47:45,278
A lot has happened, especially in Murdoch.

680
00:47:45,320 --> 00:47:48,039
- Do you remember Union Street?
- Mm-hm.

681
00:47:48,080 --> 00:47:52,551
Well, they've changed the name.
Now it's called lwo Jima Boulevard.

682
00:47:52,600 --> 00:47:55,751
- That's news.
- And there was a post office scandal.

683
00:47:55,800 --> 00:47:59,395
- Yeah?
- About the new mural in the post office.

684
00:47:59,440 --> 00:48:02,000
The town collected $2,000 to hire a painter.

685
00:48:02,040 --> 00:48:05,191
The mayor got his cousin
from Chicago to do it.

686
00:48:05,240 --> 00:48:07,435
- That's nice.
- It was 80 feet long.

687
00:48:07,480 --> 00:48:09,357
Supposed to be Custer's last stand.

688
00:48:09,400 --> 00:48:12,995
After the cousin left town,
they found out it wasn't an original.

689
00:48:13,040 --> 00:48:15,679
He copied the whole thing from a beer ad.

690
00:48:15,720 --> 00:48:17,153
(Pringle) Hm.

691
00:48:17,200 --> 00:48:21,557
- There was an awful lot of trouble.
- You take lowa seriously, don't you?

692
00:48:21,600 --> 00:48:23,955
Yes, I guess I do. I like it. Don't you?

693
00:48:24,000 --> 00:48:25,433
Mm-hm.

694
00:48:25,480 --> 00:48:28,870
We won a lot of honours last year,
all the 4H prizes.

695
00:48:28,920 --> 00:48:30,512
It's getting a little chilly.

696
00:48:30,560 --> 00:48:33,950
We had the lowest juvenile delinquency rate
until two months ago.

697
00:48:34,000 --> 00:48:35,069
What happened?

698
00:48:35,120 --> 00:48:38,271
A boy in Des Moines took
a blowtorch to his grandmother.

699
00:48:38,320 --> 00:48:41,471
We fell clear down to 16th place.
It was humiliating.

700
00:48:41,520 --> 00:48:43,431
(Horn honks)

701
00:48:50,840 --> 00:48:52,671
(Key clinks)

702
00:48:52,720 --> 00:48:54,312
What's that?

703
00:48:54,360 --> 00:48:57,079
- Crickets.
- Something dropped.

704
00:48:57,120 --> 00:48:59,680
- How's that?
- Something metallic.

705
00:48:59,720 --> 00:49:01,517
Metallic?

706
00:49:06,920 --> 00:49:08,717
Look, it's a key.

707
00:49:08,760 --> 00:49:10,955
A key? Whatever for?

708
00:49:11,000 --> 00:49:14,151
Evidently the man honks the horn
and that's the signal.

709
00:49:14,200 --> 00:49:16,555
You know more about
these things than I do.

710
00:49:16,600 --> 00:49:18,591
(Erika) Johnny? Johnny?

711
00:49:23,360 --> 00:49:25,351
Where are you, Johnny?

712
00:49:26,160 --> 00:49:27,593
Johnny?

713
00:49:31,240 --> 00:49:34,391
- Johnny.
- There are a lot of Johnnys in the army.

714
00:49:34,440 --> 00:49:36,635
- Now we're getting someplace.
- Where?

715
00:49:36,680 --> 00:49:39,831
This eliminates all the Jims,
the Bobs and the Georges.

716
00:49:39,880 --> 00:49:41,871
Too bad his name isn't Zachary.

717
00:49:41,920 --> 00:49:43,911
Yes, that would simplify it.

718
00:49:43,960 --> 00:49:45,996
(Door opening)

719
00:49:58,360 --> 00:49:59,759
Johnny.

720
00:50:02,560 --> 00:50:05,552
I... don't know who you refer to.

721
00:50:05,600 --> 00:50:07,192
I am Captain Pringle

722
00:50:07,240 --> 00:50:11,358
and I have with me a member
of the Congress of the United States.

723
00:50:12,400 --> 00:50:14,197
Good evening.

724
00:50:14,240 --> 00:50:17,038
- You are Erika von Schltow?
- I am.

725
00:50:17,080 --> 00:50:20,709
We have reason to believe you're
consorting with a member of our army.

726
00:50:20,760 --> 00:50:24,230
- You have?
- We think you're expecting him now.


